#MEM id=cohort-analysis source=/root/yvon/agent-department/Marketing/kai/skills/custom/cohort-analysis/SKILL.md
M|cohort-analysis|name: cohort-analysis
M|cohort-analysis|description: Kai's cohort retention analysis framework for Hourbour (SaaS) and Novizio (e-commerce). Covers cohort table structure, churn calculation, trial-to-paid funnel, LTV projection from cohort 
M|cohort-analysis|version: 1.0.0
M|cohort-analysis|Hourbour's North Star is MRR + trial-to-paid conversion. Flat averages hide cohort-level decay. A 10% average churn rate can mask a 30% churn rate in the first 30 days with 2% thereafter — those two b
M|cohort-analysis|- Any analysis of Hourbour retention, churn, or LTV
M|cohort-analysis|- Monthly Hourbour health rv
M|cohort-analysis|- When Felix models runway and needs cohort-based LTV inputs
M|cohort-analysis|- When Nate designs a churn-prevention experiment and needs baseline cohort data
M|cohort-analysis|Group users by the week they converted from trial to paid.
M|cohort-analysis|```sql
M|cohort-analysis|-- Supabase: trial-to-paid cohorts (replace table names with actual schema)
M|cohort-analysis|SELECT
M|cohort-analysis|DATE_TRUNC('week', trial_started_at) AS cohort_week,
M|cohort-analysis|COUNT(*) AS trial_starts,
M|cohort-analysis|COUNT(CASE WHEN converted_at IS NOT NULL THEN 1 END) AS conversions,
M|cohort-analysis|ROUND(100.0 * COUNT(CASE WHEN converted_at IS NOT NULL THEN 1 END) / COUNT(*), 1) AS conversion_rate_pct
M|cohort-analysis|FROM hourbour_users
M|cohort-analysis|GROUP BY cohort_week
M|cohort-analysis|ORDER BY cohort_week DESC
M|cohort-analysis|LIMIT 12;
M|cohort-analysis|```
M|cohort-analysis|For each cohort, measure what % of paying users remain active at M1, M2, M3, M6.
M|cohort-analysis|```
M|cohort-analysis|Cohort Week | M0 (100%) | M1 | M2 | M3 | M6
M|cohort-analysis|2026-W20    | 100       | 72 | 61 | 55 | 48
M|cohort-analysis|2026-W19    | 100       | 68 | 57 | 51 | —
M|cohort-analysis|```
M|cohort-analysis|**Red flag:** If M1 retention drops below 65%, the onboarding is broken — not the product. Route to Nate.
M|cohort-analysis|**Red flag:** If M1 is strong but M3 drops sharply, the product has a value cliff — route to Marcus.
M|cohort-analysis|Do not use flat churn rate for LTV. Use the cohort retention curve.
M|cohort-analysis|```
M|cohort-analysis|LTV = ARPU × Σ(retention_rate_at_month_n) for n = 1 to 24
M|cohort-analysis|= ARPU × (M1 + M2 + M3 + ... + M24)
M|cohort-analysis|```
M|cohort-analysis|If only 6 months of data exist, project M7–M24 using the M3→M6 decay slope.
M|cohort-analysis|Flag the projection as estimated beyond the data window.
M|cohort-analysis|**Always give Felix a range, not a point estimate:**
M|cohort-analysis|```
M|cohort-analysis|LTV estimate: $[low] – $[high]
M|cohort-analysis|Based on: [n] months of cohort data (M1–M6)
M|cohort-analysis|Projection method: linear decay from M3→M6 slope
M|cohort-analysis|Confidence: [LOW | MED | HIGH] depending on cohort sample size
M|cohort-analysis|```
M|cohort-analysis|For Novizio (e-commerce), cohorts are by first purchase month:
M|cohort-analysis|```
M|cohort-analysis|Cohort Month | Orders | Repeat 60d | Repeat 90d | AOV avg
M|cohort-analysis|2026-04      | 142    | 18%        | 24%        | £84
M|cohort-analysis|2026-03      | 98     | 22%        | 31%        | £91
M|cohort-analysis|```
M|cohort-analysis|**Key metrics:**
M|cohort-analysis|- **Repeat purchase rate at 60 days:** below 15% = weak retention
M|cohort-analysis|- **AOV trend:** if AOV drops over time for a cohort, product-market fit is weakening
M|cohort-analysis|- **Cohort GMV:** which acquisition month generates the most lifetime revenue?
M|cohort-analysis|Every cohort report to Marcus or Felix uses this structure:
M|cohort-analysis|```
M|cohort-analysis|COHORT REPORT — [vtr] — [date]
M|cohort-analysis|1. DATA WINDOW:   [earliest cohort] to [latest cohort] — [n] months
M|cohort-analysis|2. CONVERSION:    Trial-to-paid [X%] — [vs prior 4-week avg: +/-X%]
M|cohort-analysis|3. M1 RETENTION:  [X%] — [RED/AMBER/GREEN vs 65% threshold]
M|cohort-analysis|4. LTV ESTIMATE:  $[low]–$[high] — [confidence level]
M|cohort-analysis|5. KEY SIGNAL:    [one insight — what the cohort data says that a flat average hides]
M|cohort-analysis|6. ROUTE:         [who needs to act on this: Nate (onboarding) / Marcus (str) / Felix (model update)]
M|cohort-analysis|```
M|cohort-analysis|- Never report a single churn rate without breaking it by cohort week
M|cohort-analysis|- Never extrapolate beyond 2× the data window (6 months of data → max 12-month projection)
M|cohort-analysis|- Never report Hourbour cohort data to the Novizio ses ctx (vtr isolation rule)
M|cohort-analysis|- Never give Felix a point estimate for LTV — always a range with confidence level